##314 nervously apply hand sanitizer to your face

Wechat Ballon Park

Features, night face wall

LONDON, March 14. Before going out, I discussed with my roommate where to put my mask when I took it off outside. She said Hers could be folded up, but mine was just a wire surgical mask. So roommate relented, and I traded her the five flat valve Silverline for a foldable, reusable 3m with a valve. On the way we took off our masks where no one else was, and put them on when we started to get busy, and washed our hands with alcohol every time we touched them. Sometimes our hands would touch our cheeks, and we'd both nervously apply hand sanitizer to our faces. Foreigners sported face masks or turned turtlenecks over their mouths and noses.

Battersea walks to Victoria station and passes roadside flower and vegetable stands that don't appear until Saturday. Once past the fountains of Buckingham Palace and Green Park, crowds have dwindled, and the Mayfair Gallery in central London is likely to be closed, with posters on the doors announcing the outbreak. Thaddaeus ROPAC was still open, looking at the videos one by one, and there were very few people in the gallery. In fact, I cherish this atmosphere of business as usual, which is not quite the same as Wuhan. In fact, most people feel devastated, but still have to maintain the daily routine. I guess the equanimity in Englishness is like having a cup of tea in the bombed-out ruins. In fact, many times it is a confirmation of normal public order. It is for other people's eyes as well as for our own. The island is too small to know what greater calamity will befall it when order breaks down. So this apparent calmness may be part of the survival, but it's all about secretly buying hand sanitizer, pasta, and toilet rolls.

On the way to the Royal Academy, suddenly a paw came over and made a gesture to take off my mask, and I realized that the hand had gone over my head, i turned to see the man with his arm still propped up outside and the woman with his other arm walking forward, but also turned to look at me. I shouted, "it's not polite. "

In the RA ticket line, the British grandfather standing behind me a meter away looked at me with a smile. I asked him, "Do you find it's strange? " It seems very professional. So I gave him a lesson on the role of air valves in masks. Looking at Picasso's blue period paintings in the gallery, GRANDPA suddenly reappears and says, "It's a brilliant work! "

Read Picasso on Paper, a lot of people, to recognize several new kinds of Paper. In the evening, I went to see my friend who was stationed in this house. I found that artists from six countries who were stationed in this house were urgently contacting tour companies to book tickets back to Canada, Brazil and the Netherlands. My friend may not be able to return, because the plane ticket is too expensive.

I didn't think about going back at first, I thought it would be too much. After struggling this afternoon with the idea of being isolated for half a month, spending thirty thousand airfare and not knowing when I'll be back in the UK, I decided to stay here, read my dissertation, and rediscover the ways of London at this particular time. When you get home in the evening, Rehearse with your roommate where to put your coat and shoes, discuss how your wool coat is safe from alcohol poisoning, and imagine going out with a raincoat, hair tie, and shower cap, disposable gloves are on the way. After thinking of these a lot of peace of mind, think of my mother yesterday's question, the United Kingdom's parks grow a bitter cabbage? She obviously wants me to dig for POTHERBS.
